As large language models (LLMs) become increasingly integrated into various applications, concerns regarding the inadvertent leakage of personally identifiable information (PII) have gained significant attention. This paper analyse the inherent risks associated with fine-tuning on extensive datasets that may contain PII and examine the implications of model outputs. We explore two different privacy attacks on various LLM architectures. Furthermore, we explore mitigation strategies, including data scrubbing and differential privacy in fine-tuning process. Our findings illustrate even with those mitigation techniques these powerful models could still ensuring that user privacy is prioritized without compromising the utility of these powerful models. This work aims to inform researchers and practitioners about the critical balance between leveraging LLM capabilities and safeguarding sensitive information.